Ahead of World Refugee Day on June 20th, Safe Haven wants to hear from you on how this community has positively impacted your life. Follow the hashtag #DecreaseStigmaIncreaseConnectionsForRefugees to learn more!

node.text:
For more than a decade, 14-year-old Peterson has been living with the scars of tragedy.  In January 2010, a magnitude 7.0 earthquake struck Haiti, claiming the lives of more than 220,000 people and destroying much of the country’s infrastructure. But – only 4 years old at the time – he doesn’t remember any of it: “They told me I spent three days buried in the rubble." He lost his arm as a result.⁠
⁠
Both Peterson and his godmother weren't injured in last month's devastating quake, but their home was badly damaged. However, despite everything, the support he's received at a UNICEF-supported center has given him a renewed sense of hope for the future. “My dream is to be an artist and actor, and be on the internet,” Peterson says. “To realize my dream, I’ll have to work very hard, starting from now. While I’m young, I should start doing the work so that I can grow.”⁠
⁠
To read more about his story of resilience, check out our link in bio.

10-year-old Jamiatul is excited to be back in her classroom in Cox's Bazar, #Bangladesh after a very long absence. Just this week, schools across the country reopened for the first time in 18 months!

#ForEveryChild, education.

📸: @unicefbangladesh

node.text: Some much-needed moments of joy at a mobile Child-Friendly Space in a settlement for displaced people in Herat, #Afghanistan. These recreational and learning opportunities offer a chance for kids to just be kids again after the past few tumultuous weeks. UNICEF teams are also on the ground providing essential services, including mental health counseling.

In Uganda, Mary Kiiza goes door-to-door talking to residents of Buhura Parish about efforts to combat the second wave of the pandemic. UNICEF works with #COVID19 task forces like Mary's to actively engage communities, focusing on limiting misinformation and slowing the spread of the virus. Together, we can #EndThePandemic.

📸: @unicefuganda

node.text:
For health worker Tamara Katuli, getting the #COVID19 vaccine means she can provide the best possible care for babies and children in Blantyre, Malawi. "This vaccine is good," she says. "It helped us because at first we were afraid of COVID-19. After getting vaccinated, we felt safe and happy."

📸: @unicefmalawi

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by UNICEF USA on September 13, 2021. May be an image of 2 people and indoor.

node.text:
Pandemic-related school closures have affected 4.3 million students in Ecuador — drastically impacting their learning, development, and mental health. But teachers like Luis Carlos have spent this time learning how to best support their students digitally.

"There are children who are going through situations that we are unaware of," he says. "Some families have gone through very difficult economic situations and we may not be able to help them financially, but we can support them emotionally."

📸: @unicefecuador

node.text:
With the pandemic deeply affecting education around the world, schools across #DRCongo have shortened the holiday break in order to make up for missed lessons - with classes starting in October. But students like these two friends don't seem to mind, as they can soon get back to spending their days together!

#ForEveryChild, learning.
📸: @unicefrdcongo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by UNICEF USA on September 10, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and indoor.

node.text:
For 18-year-old Julissa, the pandemic took away major milestones like senior prom and a traditional graduation ceremony. And one week into New York City’s lockdown, both of Julissa’s parents contracted #COVID19. "At the deepest point, I just felt like my depression was gonna last forever," she says.⁠
⁠
At our link in bio, read her story of overcoming adversity.⁠
⁠
📸: Peter Van Agtmael for Magnum Photos

On the second International Day to #ProtectEducationFromAttack, we are proud to work with @educationaboveall_eaa to ensure kids across the world can have the opportunity to realize their dreams.

A child's right to education does not change because of conflict and crisis.
📸: @unicefbrasil
